<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Sterea Ellas: Biotia (Boeotia), Mt. Kitheron, c.1400m, 19 V 2013, 1♂; 20 VI 2015, 8♂, 1♀. Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Poecilimon propinquus, Sterea Ellas, Mt. Kitheron, 19 V 2013. A. pronotum, B. tip of abdomen, C. habitus, D. collection locality with scattered bushes of Daphne, E. habitus." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.26.14541.1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/142161" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1A-E</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
New for Biotia and Mt. Kitheron. The male cerci (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Poecilimon propinquus, Sterea Ellas, Mt. Kitheron, 19 V 2013. A. pronotum, B. tip of abdomen, C. habitus, D. collection locality with scattered bushes of Daphne, E. habitus." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.26.14541.1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/142161" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1B</figureCitation>
) and the female basal fold of our material agrees with the figures published in 
<bibRefCitation author="Willemse, F" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" refId="B22" refString="Willemse, F, 1982. A survey of the Greek species of Poecilimon Fischer (Orthoptera, Ensifera, Phaneropterinae). Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 125: 155-203." title="A survey of the Greek species of Poecilimon Fischer (Orthoptera, Ensifera, Phaneropterinae). Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 125: 155 - 203." year="1982">Willemse (1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Willemse, F" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" refId="B25" refString="Willemse, F, 1986. A key to the Orthoptera species of Greece. Fauna Graeciae II: 1-288." title="A key to the Orthoptera species of Greece. Fauna Graeciae II: 1 - 288." year="1986">1986</bibRefCitation>
). This is the first member of this genus to be collected from Mt. Kitheron. This mountain ridge forms the borders between Attiki and Biotia. The collection locality is on the northern slope of the mountain summit, which belongs to Biotia (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Poecilimon propinquus, Sterea Ellas, Mt. Kitheron, 19 V 2013. A. pronotum, B. tip of abdomen, C. habitus, D. collection locality with scattered bushes of Daphne, E. habitus." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.26.14541.1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/142161" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1D</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poecilimon propinquus" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="propinquus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Poecilimon propinquus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to CE mainland Greece (Attiki and NE Peloponnisos), Evvia and some offshore island (Egina, Spetses, Makronisos) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 2. Total known distribution of Poecilimon propinquus (• literature localities, ▲ new locality)." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.26.14541.4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/142162" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2</figureCitation>
). The species is known from several localities of Attiki (Parnitha, Imittos, Sounion, Boula), most of them on the north and eastern side (
<bibRefCitation author="Willemse, F" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" refId="B23" refString="Willemse, F, 1984. Catalogue of the Orthoptera of Greece. Fauna Graeciae 1: 1-275." title="Catalogue of the Orthoptera of Greece. Fauna Graeciae 1: 1 - 275." year="1984">Willemse 1984</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Willemse, F" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" refId="B24" refString="Willemse, F, 1985. Supplementary notes on the Orthoptera of Greece. Fauna Graeciae 1a: 1-47." title="Supplementary notes on the Orthoptera of Greece. Fauna Graeciae 1 a: 1 - 47." year="1985">1985</bibRefCitation>
). The only, yet unpublished, locality from W Attiki, is at Aigosthena, 5 km east of Porto Germenos, not far from Mt. Kitheron (Lehmann and Lehmann unpubl. 2002, A. Lehmann pers. comm. 2017). This is the fourth member of the genus known so far from Biotia, the other three being 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. gerlindae" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="gerlindae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">P. gerlindae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lehmann, Willemse and Heller, 2006, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. obesus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="obesus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">P. obesus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878 and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. zimmeri" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="zimmeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">P. zimmeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ramme, 1933, occurring mostly on the west side of Biotia, Mt. Parnassos.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lehmann, A. W., F. M. H. Willemse &amp; K. - G. Heller" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poecilimon gerlindae" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gerlindae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Poecilimon gerlindae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from Domokos, Nomos Pthiotidos and it belongs to the 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. propinquus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="propinquus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">P. propinquus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Its southernmost known locality is Aliartos and Ipsilantis at the heart of Biotian valley. Our locality, only a few km to the south, is obviously situated on, or very close to, the borderline of these two closely related species. Although morphologically very similar, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. propinquus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="propinquus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">P. propinquus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can easily be separated by the shape of the male cerci and female basal fold (
<bibRefCitation author="Lehmann, AW" journalOrPublisher="Articulata" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="109 - 119" refId="B13" refString="Lehmann, AW, Willemse, F, Heller, K-G, 2006. Poecilimon gerlindae spec. nov.-a new bushcricket species of the Poecilimon propinquus -group (Orthoptera: Phaneropteridae) from Greece. Articulata 21: 109 - 119" title="Poecilimon gerlindae spec. nov. - a new bushcricket species of the Poecilimon propinquus - group (Orthoptera: Phaneropteridae) from Greece." volume="21" year="2006">Lehmann et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
The population of Mt. Kitheron seems to be localized. This is the situation also on Mt. Imittos, the type locality of the species, where 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. propinquus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="propinquus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">P. propinquus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also found in single sites (
<bibRefCitation author="Lehmann, GUC" journalOrPublisher="Articulata" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" refId="B14" refString="Lehmann, GUC, Frommolt, KH, Lehmann, AW, Riede, K, 2014. Baseline data for automated acoustic monitoring of Orthoptera in a Mediterranean landscape, the Hymettos, Greece. Journal of Insect Conservation 18: 909-925." title="Baseline data for automated acoustic monitoring of Orthoptera in a Mediterranean landscape, the Hymettos, Greece. Journal of Insect Conservation 18: 909 - 925." year="2014">Lehmann et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Several attempts, in several years, by the author to locate more populations were in vain. All the specimens were collected from an area of a few square meters, a rocky slope dominated by 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Thymelaeaceae" genus="Daphne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Daphne oleoides" order="Thymelaeales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="oleoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Daphne oleoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shrubs, facing the famous Biotian valley (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Poecilimon propinquus, Sterea Ellas, Mt. Kitheron, 19 V 2013. A. pronotum, B. tip of abdomen, C. habitus, D. collection locality with scattered bushes of Daphne, E. habitus." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.26.14541.1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/142161" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">1D</figureCitation>
). All insects were found on the 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Thymelaeaceae" genus="Daphne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Daphne" order="Thymelaeales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Daphne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shrubs, except for a female found moving on the ground.
</paragraph>
